reviewText: Bramwell is one of the best series to have ever been aired on television for what might at first glance seem to be a trivial reason--its protaganist is a well-rounded, entirely admirable yet flawed, capable, intelligent, insistent, compassionate, and attractive young woman. Good women are hard to find in television, and its even harder to find a female protaganist (whose show is named after her) who is not more interested in alcohol than food, sex than her career, fashion than family. I urge Acorn to release the entire Bramwell series on DVD. My local library has an incomplete video collection and I and my friends are eager to purchase the series for ourselves. Our daughters need good female role models, and in t.v., those are few and far between.

reviewText: I have wanted to own this series since I saw it on Masterpiece Theatre several years ago.  My daughter and my husband gave me part of the set for Christmas - I finished up the set for myself.  I enjoyed watching every minute of it and look forward to watching it again and again.  If you have never seen this series, I highly recommend it for anyone interested in the Edwardian England lifestyle - and especially for those interested in women's struggle for equality.  Eleanor Bramwell overcame enormous obstacles and prejudices to live her life as a doctor.
